YouTube got a boost from election ads; Search, meanwhile, is holding steady=
 from a revenue perspective, while management commentary was fairly optimis=
tic on a few key questions. First, CBO Philipp Schindler was asked about se=
arch volume:

On Search usage overall, our metrics are healthy. We are continuing to see =
growth in Search on a year-on-year basis in terms of overall usage. Of cour=
se, within that, AI overviews has seen stronger growth, particularly across=
 all segments of users, including in younger users. So it's being well rece=
ived. But overall, I think through this AI moment, I think Search is contin=
uing to perform well. And as I said earlier, we have a lot more innovations=
 to come this year. I think the product will evolve even more. And I think =
as you make Search, as you give, as you make it more easy for people to int=
eract and ask follow-up questions, et cetera, I think we have an opportunit=
y to drive further growth.

Second, CEO Sundar Pichai once again claimed that AI overviews drive more s=
earch volume:

Our Products and Platforms put AI into the hands of billions of people arou=
nd the world. We have seven Products and Platforms with over 2 billion user=
s and all are using Gemini. That includes Search, where Gemini is powering =
our AI overviews. People use Search more with AI overviews and usage growth=
 increases over time as people learn that they can ask new types of questio=
ns. This behavior is even more pronounced with younger users who really app=
reciate the speed and efficiency of this new format.

Third, Schindler reported positive results for AI search overview advertisi=
ng:

First of all, AI overviews, which is really nice to see, continue to drive =
higher satisfaction and search usage. So, that's really good. And as you kn=
ow, we recently launched the ads within AI overviews on mobile in the U.S.,=
 which builds on our previous rollout of ads above and below. And as I talk=
ed about before, for the AI overviews overall, we actually see monetization=
 at approximately the same rate, which I think really gives us a strong bas=
e on which we can innovate even more.

For all of the handwringing about AI's potentially disruptive impact on Goo=
gle Search, the evidence we have continues to suggest that Google is handli=
ng it well: revenue is steady, AI overviews are being used, and critically,=
 they are monetizing without cannibalizing revenue. This is all good news! =
If Google can maintain something approaching a steady state in Search they =
should be afforded the time to figure out all of the other ways that they m=
ight be able to monetize AI =E2=80=94 and should be able to build data cent=
ers to do so.

There is one other Search worry that I've been thinking about, though: the =
continued diminishment in quality content on the open web. Part of this is =
AI slop, and part of this is just the sense that things have been getting w=
orse, as SEO slop overwhelms quality content that undergirds Google Search.

