The much more pertinent investigation was just reported a couple of hours a=
go; from Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2025-02-05/chi=
na-weighs-investigating-apple-over-app-store-policies-fees-including-30-cut=
 ) :

China=E2=80=99s antitrust watchdog is laying the groundwork for a potential=
 probe into Apple Inc.=E2=80=99s policies and the fees it charges app devel=
opers, part of a broader push by Beijing that risks becoming another flashp=
oint in the country=E2=80=99s trade war with the US. The State Administrati=
on for Market Regulation is examining Apple=E2=80=99s policies, which inclu=
de taking a cut of as much as 30% on in-app spending and barring external p=
ayment services and stores, people familiar with the matter said. Agency of=
ficials have spoken with Apple executives and app developers since last yea=
r, said the people, who asked for anonymity to discuss sensitive moves.

The conversations stem from long-running disputes between Apple and develop=
ers such as Tencent Holdings Ltd. and ByteDance Ltd. over iOS store policie=
s =E2=80=94 a source of tension between the US company and regulators world=
wide. While Beijing has since 2024 targeted the practices of US tech firms =
from Nvidia Corp. to most recently Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s Google, regulato=
rs may not formally move against Apple if the current conversations go well=
.

This does, for the record, seem to be a much more legitimate investigation =
that (1) has real stakes, because Apple does operate the App Store in China=
, (2) appears to have started a long time ago, and (3) is a legitimate thin=
g to investigate! What is curious is this bit of news from last fall in the=
 South China Morning Post ( https://www.scmp.com/tech/big-tech/article/3287=
430/apple-reveals-app-store-revenue-share-china-huawei-rivalry-grows ) :

Apple has made a rare disclosure of the revenue generated from its App Stor=
e in China, as the US tech giant grapples with a controversy surrounding th=
e so-called Apple Tax =E2=80=93 commission fees that the company charges de=
velopers for using its app store and in-app payment system. Apple China on =
Monday published an article on its official website that cited a report by =
a Shanghai University of Finance and Economics researcher, saying that the =
local App Store paid over 95 per cent of the 3.76 trillion yuan (US$519 bil=
lion) in revenue it generated last year to Chinese developers and various c=
ompanies.

I wasn't able to find the report in question =E2=80=94 please forward it to=
 me if you have it =E2=80=94 so I'm not sure how Apple is calculating that =
95%; the App Store's commission rates in China are not =E2=80=94 as far as =
I know =E2=80=94 lower, so I'm not sure what is going on.

Regardless, this is an investigation to keep an eye on, and whether or not =
it's related to a trade war, that certainly doesn't help Apple's case.

